Motivation

Department of Housing and Community Development (DHC)s Home Repair Tax Credit Program is a program that help enhance the social good by offering those households in need credits to repair their homes. By doing so, the house value of these households as well as the surrounding houses will all go up due to the spillover effect. All these enhancement will lead to rise in the neighborhood aesthetics, safety, land development, economic activities and thus higher overall tax revenue in this area. The increased tax revenue can then be applied to generate more public good and further raise the social welfare. Given the great benefits that this program can bring to the society, DHCs goal is to provide all the needed households with this tax credit. To better promote this program, marketing materials are distributed to attract these potential households, regardless of the costs that the DHC needs to pay.

Data Visualization

The result of the prior campaign indicates that there are significantly fewer number of homeowners taking the subsidy credits than those not (Figure 1.1). This class imbalance can seriously affect out model performance, which will be further illustrated later in this memo.

ggplot(mutate(housingsubsidy, tookSubsidy = fct_infreq(tookSubsidy))) + geom_bar(aes(x = tookSubsidy), fill = "#d24ae8") +
  labs(title = "Figure 1.1: Results of Prior Campaigns", x = "Repair Credit Uptake Among Contacted Homeowners", y = "Count of Homeowners") +
  plotTheme()

Among all the features we have for prediction, for continuous variables, people are more likely to accept the subsidy when they are older, contacted for this campaign fewer times but much more frequently contacted before this campaign, had a sooner follow-up from a previous program, and are going through a time with high consumer confident index, and low inflation and unemployment rates at the campaign time.

For categorical variables, people are more likely to accept the subsidy when they use a cell phone instead of a telephone, have a university degree, have a administrative job, didnt participate or successfully participated in the last campaign, have a mortgage, are married and are full-time residents in Philadelphia.

Its interesting that people who spend more annually on housing repairs dont have a higher tendency in participating in this tax credit program. This suggests that our current practice to attract potential house owners is not accurate enough and needs to be refined.

The features that contribute most to the distinction between house owners accepting the subsidy and owners not are unemployment and inflation rates, as well as the number of contacts before this campaign for continuous variables, and residency location, participation in previous campaign, device for contact, job and marital status for categorical variables.

Refining the Prediction Model

Engineer new features

Six new features are added, including employment status, age group, education degree group, working industry, time from last contact and if contacted before.

The original job data generates the employment status (unemployed, retired, student, employed) and working industry two new features, based on the assumption that people who are out of job or are in certain industries earn less money or have less time for home repairing, thus are more in need of the tax credits.

The original data of age generates a new feature by being divided into groups (young adult, middle-aged adult and old adult), based on the assumption that people in certain stage of life are more in need of housing thus the maintenance of the housing.

The original education data generates the new feature of degree group, based on the assumption that people with lower than college degree are likely earn less and therefore are more in need of the subsidy.

Finally, we use contact information to generate two new features lastContact (never contacted, 1-2 weeks, 2-3 weeks and more than 3 weeks) and contactedBefore (yes or no), based on the assumption that people who are contacted before or more frequently contacted have a higher chance of accepting the subsidy because they are more aware of this program and are more likely to be convinced.

housingsubsidy <- 
  housingsubsidy %>% 
  mutate(employStatus = case_when(job == "unemployed"  ~ "unemployed",
                                   job == "retired" ~ "retired",
                                  job == "student" ~ "student",
                                   TRUE  ~ "employed"),
         ageGroup = case_when(age >= 18 & age < 35 ~ "Young adult",
                                   age >= 35 & age < 65  ~ "Middle-aged adult",
                                   age >= 65  ~ "Old adult"), 
         degreeGroup = case_when(education == "high.school" ~ "high school",
                                   education == "university.degree" ~ "bachelor's",
                                   education == "unknown" ~ "unknown",
                                  education == "illiterate" ~ "illiterate",
                                  TRUE ~ "Below high school"),
         industry = case_when(job == "blue-collar" | job == "technician" ~ "blue collar",
                              job == "services" | job == "housemaid" ~ "services",
                              job == "entrepreneur" | job == "self-employed" ~ "entrepreneur",
                              job == "admin." | job == "management" ~ "white collar",
                              TRUE ~ "Unknown"),
         lastContact = case_when(pdays == 999 ~ "never contacted",
                                 pdays < 7 ~ "Past week",
                                 pdays >= 7 & pdays < 14 ~ "1-2 Weeks",
                                 pdays >= 14 & pdays < 21 ~ "2-3 Weeks",
                               TRUE ~ "More than 3 Weeks"),
         contactedBefore = case_when(previous == 0 ~ "no",
                                  TRUE ~ "yes"))

Building the model with new features

After we have all the new features added to the original data, we divide it into training set and testing set.

Results

Cross validate both models

After cross validating both models, we now have two plots of ROC, Sensitivity and Specificity (Figure 3.1). Adding new features improve both the classification performance (ROC), the models ability to successfully predict those who receive the subsidy (sensitivity) and the models ability to predict those who refuse to receive the subsidy (specificity). Notwithstanding, the sensitivity is still too low for an accurate and useful model, because there arent enough cases of people accepting the subsidy in the data, namely the class imbalance mentioned above.

Interpret the ROC curve

The ROC curve shows the trade-off between sensitivity and specificity. A random classifier is expected to give points along the diagonal (0.5 area under the curve). Our new model is better off since its further from the diagonal and has bigger area under the curve. However, its not close enough to the top-left corner, where the true positive fraction (predict correctly of those who accept the subsidy) is the highest and the false positive fraction (predict incorrectly of those who accept the subsidy) is the lowest (Figure 4.1).

## Area under the curve: 0.7714

Cost benefit analysis

There are four confusion metrics and their cost/benefit equations are presented below.

True Negative - The cost/benefit is 0 in this case, because no credits nor market resources are accepted or allocated.
True Positive - The cost benefit here should be calculated separately as the following: ((10,000 - 7,850) * (Count * .25)) + ((-2,850) * (Count * .75)). The $2,850 market allocation each is fixed no matter the credit is accepted or not, however, for those who accept the credit, even with an addtional credit cost of $5,000 each, we would still have an $ 10,000 house value premium each adding to the public good.
False Negative - The cost/benefit is 0, because no credits nor market resources are accepted or allocated through DHC.
False Positive - The cost/benefit is (-2,850)*Count, because although we are wrong about the prediction, we spend $2,850 each on market allocation already.

The cost/benefit analysis above only applies to individual home and the spillover effect of $56,000 is not included. Its because $56,000 is just an estimated number, and the spillover effect in reality is highly likely be affected by the size of the neighborhood as well as the distance of the house with its surrounding houses.

The final Cost/Benefit table is shown in table 2. We are expected to lose 62.4k in the True-positive case and 57k in the False-positive case.

cost_benefit_table <-
   testProbs_r2 %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),

                         Variable == "False_Negative" ~ 0 * Count,

As the threshold for classifying house owners taking the subsidy or not goes up, the market allocation plus the credit costs of DHC are gradually offset by the increase of house owners housing value (Figure 5.1). Table 3 shows that at the threshold of 0.96 and up, the costs are even with the benefits. Neglecting the spillover effect here results in higher threshold than costs/benefits analysis including this effect.

iterateThresholds <- function(data) {
  x = .01
  all_prediction <- data.frame()
  while (x <= 1) {
  
  this_prediction <-
      testProbs_r2 %>%
      mutate(predOutcome = ifelse(Probs > x, 1, 0)) %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
     gather(Variable, Count) %>%
     mutate(Revenue =
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Negative", Count * 0,
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive",((10000 - 7850) * (Count * .25)) + (-2850 * (Count * .75)),
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", 0 * Count,
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Positive", (-2850) * Count, 0)))), 
            Threshold = x)
  
  all_prediction <- rbind(all_prediction, this_prediction)
  x <- x + .01
  }
return(all_prediction)
}

whichThreshold <- iterateThresholds(testProbs_r2)

whichThreshold_revenue <- 
whichThreshold %>% 
    group_by(Threshold) %>% 
    summarize(Revenue = sum(Revenue))

    mutate(actualcreditno = ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive", (Count * .75), ifelse(Variable == "False_Positive", Count, 0)),
           actualcredityes = ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive", (Count * .25), ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", Count, 0))) %>%  
    group_by(Threshold) %>% 
    summarize(Revenue = sum(Revenue),
              sumcredityes = sum(actualcredityes))

At the threshold of 0.96, we have 168 house owners accepting the credits and the costs of DHC are made even by the increased housing values. Thats to say, the DHCs efforts are properly rewarded by the growth in housing value and the social good. However at the threshold of 0.5, there are more costs than gains. However, in reality, this threshold can be slightly lower due to the existence of the spillover effect.

Conclusions

This model with new features should be put into production because it has a better classification performance, and higher accuracy in predicting both house owners accepting and refusing tax credits compared to the kitchen-sink model. The new threshold (0.96) makes possible that the costs of DHC are properly rewarded by the gains in housing value premium. More tax revenue can be generated from this process and be put into producing more public good.

Since the models power to predict individuals who will accept the credits (sensitivity) is low, and is mostly caused by limited positive cases in the original data set, resetting the scale of data collection so that there is higher ratio of positive cases should significantly improve the model. Other than this, finding and engineering more effective features in prediction can also help improve the overall accuracy and generality of the model.

Lastly, to make sure that the marketing materials have a better response rate, we can reset a higher threshold while improving our models sensitivity at the same time. The response rate is supposed to climb as our prediction power goes up.
